Latin America in the Fight Against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented magnitude and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not decisively confront the crisis, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political responses in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
Other governments, on the other hand, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided false information to their citizens, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose populist and divisive policies in the midst of the tragedy.
Latin America's first priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Policymakers must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
In addition, Latin American countries must reject export controls on medical supplies and other critical resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to U.S. President Donald Trump, who unilaterally froze contributions of about 500 million dollars to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only was Latin American domestic production disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to the absence of tourism, fewer remittances from abroad, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for businesses are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and wage-related costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Therefore, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system—and with it the entire economy—is at risk.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the shortage of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment postponements, and subsidized loans will not be sufficient.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented loan guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue lending, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state banks can play a leading role.
In general, although the measures will vary from country to country, extraordinary budget resources will likely be needed everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without exacerbating the health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is today even tighter than after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, fiscal burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
In this context, there is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can, however, be reduced by the governments' promise to correct the higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, external support for households and balance of payments is urgently needed, particularly for the small and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and states take on higher deficits, the countries' current account balances are likely to deteriorate.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the history of modern financial markets – are exacerbating the problem further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
Here the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
He must attend to the short-term currency and budget needs of the countries and continue to support the economies through this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
For this, he needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a revival of the IMF's global reserve currency—the Special Drawing Rights (SDR)—which should reach a volume of one trillion SDR.
Although the SDR are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the fund's supervision.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity to meet the upcoming strong credit demand by immediately doubling the volume of the New Credit Agreements.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-threshold instruments with rapid disbursement—such as its Rapid Financing Instrument—or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs are not being approved in a timely manner.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps—either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
In the domestic sphere, central banks must use all instruments at their disposal and, if necessary, create new ones to supply the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net lending in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide further fiscal support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit disbursement could be supplemented by a debt restructuring.
The MDBs should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
In this case, time plays a decisive role.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unprecedented in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and demonstrate what it can offer its citizens.
